      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be less than 5% for primary QoI (hemolysis index) across all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed (3.2M, 6.8M, 14.1M cells). GCI for hemolysis index ranged from 1.8% to 3.4% across all 5 operating points, satisfying the 5% threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirms second-order convergence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must match simulated operating conditions within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data collected at flow rates 2.5–6 L/min and rotational speeds 2000–3500 RPM. CFD boundary conditions set to match experimental conditions within ±2% for flow rate and ±10 RPM for rotational speed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index values must agree with experimental measurements within 25% across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index predictions compared against five independent experimental datasets from FDA benchmark study. Mean absolute error of 14.3% observed; maximum deviation 22.7% at highest flow rate condition. All points within acceptance band."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantities of interest used in validation (hemolysis index, shear stress distribution) must directly correspond to the clinical decision metric (relative hemolysis index RH).",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and power-law hemolysis model outputs map directly to the relative hemolysis index RH used in the acceptance criterion. Scalar hemolysis index is the primary QoI in both validation and COU contexts."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
